@node Doc.OutOfDateIndex "IceIQle, Doc: OutOfDateIndex"
Detection of out of date Index Files
------------------------------------

After editing a phrase file, an already existing index file will
now be out of date. If you don't either delete the index or manually
regenerate it, the next time that particular phrase file is used you
will be presented with the Phrase file @{" Count/Update " link Doc.CountingIndex 21} requester which
will allow you to regenerate the index. This works by comparing the
date stamp of the phrase file with that of the index. If the index
is older, it is considered out of date.

When using the %S control with an index file, everytime %S is used, it
must update the next sequential value to use by writing into the phrase
file. This changes the date stamp to the current time which would make
a valid index "out of date". To get around this problem, the date stamp
of the index is also set to the current date immediately after %S is used.

@endnode

@node Doc.QuotingDescription "IceIQle, Doc: QuotingDescription"
HOW IceIQle's QUOTING WORKS
---------------------------

   ·  Initials are formed by examining the 'Author:' and 'Address:' lines.
   ·  If there is no 'Author:' line, a 'From:' line is searched for to
      handle EMail messages. (It would appear Feedback should be covered
      by this approach, however the 'From:' line is not actually included
      in the temp file used for feedback posts/replies, so that is why
      quoting doesn't and can't work in Feedback).
   ·  Any line within the first EXCLUDENUM lines starting with any of
      the strings contained in the EXCLUDEINFO tooltype will be deleted.
   ·  The appropriate HEADER string will be outputted, if one is defined.
   ·  Any existing signature of the form KH> will not get re-indented
      with another set of initials like SV> KH> but will remain as just
      KH>
   ·  Any line determined to have no previous quoting information will
      be quoted using the 'Author' initial.
   ·  Any line that has just one '>' character without any words to its
      left will be considered a previous quote and the 'Address' initial
      will be used to quote.
   ·  Any line that has 2 '>' characters without any words to the left
      will be considered to have been quoted twice already and it is
      therefore impossible to deduce the original author. It will be
      left unchanged.
   ·  Lines like:
      > run >nil:
      that have two or more '>' chars will be examined for any 'words' to
      the left of any '>'s. Anything to the right of the left most word
      is then ignored.
      So the example above will be properly quoted with the 'Address'
      initial being used.
   ·  A line that has been quoted several times normally, but with an
      initialed quote inside like:
      > > KH>
      will get fixed to just
       KH>
   ·  If you have a TAGLINE string defined, it is outputted.
   ·  If the CLEANUP tooltype is set to TRUE, some empty lines that
      have been quoted will get converted back to empty lines to improve
      readability and separate different authors.
   ·  Your editor is called, and if it detaches from the CLI, IceIQle
      immediately exits, otherwise IceIQle waits until the editor is
      closed, then exits.

@endnode

@node Doc.Requirements "IceIQle, Doc: Requirements"
REQUIREMENTS
------------

   Works for all KickStart versions. The only exception to this is when
   using Phrase File counting and index generation from WorkBench. This
   requires KickStart V37+ (ie. WorkBench 2.0+).

@endnode

