@node Doc.What_is_it "IceIQle, Doc: What is it"
WHAT IS IT?
----------

   IceIQle can generate completely customizable taglines and signatures
   with any Off-Line based message reader that uses an external text editor,
   AND in conjunction with the IceTERM BBS software, Copyright 1993 Stephen
   Vermeulen, or AmiQWK, also provides header strings and initialed
   quoting with paragraph wordwrap. Initialed quoting is of the form:

    KH> Original Message

   It also works with IceTERM when quoting EMail and SIGS messages On-Line.

   The customized header strings, tag lines and signatures can be read
   randomly or sequentially from a text file of your favorites.



@endnode

@node Embed.CustomControls "IceIQle, Embed: CustomControls"
Custom String Embedding Controls
--------------------------------

      %n               -  Newline character
      %%               -  ONE Percent character
                          Using this is only necessary if you intend
                          to use a character combination that ends
                          up including a valid control code. A '%'
                          character followed by an undefined letter
                          (eg. ...90% of the...) is left unchanged.
      %T##             -  Horizontal Tab. ## can be 1 or 2 digits of
                          the column to tab to. 1 is left edge (not 0).
                          Useful for including constant text that needs
                          to be aligned properly to the right of
                          something variable, like a name for example.
                          If the 'cursor' is already to the right of
                          the requested position, nothing occurs.
      %C"FileName(s)"  -  Constant (Signature) file.
                          The entire text file is included.
                          Control codes in the file are NOT interpreted.
      %I"FileName(s)"  -  Interpreted Constant (Signature) file.
                          The entire text file is included.
                          Control codes in the file ARE interpreted.
      %R@"FileName(s)" -  @{" Randomly select one phrase " link CustomControls.RandomSequential} from text file.
      %S@"FileName(s)" -  @{" Sequentially select one phrase " link CustomControls.RandomSequential} from text file.
      %V"FileName(s)"  -  @{" Variable SIG dependent strings. " link CustomControls.SigDependant}  [IceBBS Only]

    You can either specify the full path with any "FileName" argument,
    or just the filename if you use the @{" PHRASEDIR " link ToolTypes.PhraseDir} tooltype. The double
    quote marks around the FileName are required. You can actually
    specify up to two filenames, each file requiring the double quotes
    around them (and NO SPACE between the quotes of the two files). If
    only one file is specified, it will always be used. If a second file
    is specified it will be used in the case where there is no Author:
    information available to IceIQle. This is primarily intended to allow
    taglines with and without embedded author names, without having posts
    (that have no author information) leaving a blank where the name is
    intended to go. The tagfile called with the second filename should
    have no embedded author type of tags. Example 3 in the
    @{" Variable SIG dependent strings " link CustomControls.SigDependant} section has an example of this.

@endnode

@node Embed.DateNameControls "IceIQle, Embed: DateNameControls"
Name/Date String Embedding controls    [IceBBS and AmiQWK Only]
-----------------------------------

                     %a       -  Author's Full Name
                                 (Or the From: person in EMail)
                     %F or %1 -  First Name of Author
                     %L       -  Last Name of Author
                     %r       -  Addressee's Full Name
                     %2       -  First Name of Addressee
                     %3       -  Last Name of Addressee
                     %s       -  Subject
                     %w       -  Weekday     (Mon, Tue...)
                     %m       -  Month       (Jan, Feb...)
                     %d       -  Day         (1, 2...)
                     %t       -  Time        (hh:mm:ss)
                     %f       -  Full Year   (eg. 1994)
                     %y       -  2 Digit Yr. (eg. 94)

      All this information is simply extracted from the proper line in
      the header of the original message. The user Creation Dates are
      used rather than the BBS dates for SIGS messages. The Date: line
      is used in EMail. Upper and Lower case % codes are obviously
      different.

@endnode

@node Installation.AmiQWK "IceIQle, Installation: AmiQWK"
AmiQWK Installation
-------------------

     · Change the Editor setup configuration of AmiQWK to
        call IceIQle, but leave the editor name in as well.

             With AmiQWK II v2.2, set the editor configuration to:

                   IceIQle Editor

        Specify the full path to IceIQle, or make sure it's on the
        search path.

      ·  Make sure you set the Quote Prefix to empty in the Config/Replies
         requester of AmiQWK.

      ·  Make sure you have the 'Header info in replies' checkbox
         checked in Config/Replies. This is necessary for IceIQle
         to extract the name/date/subject information. If you don't
         like this header in your replies, you can use the
         @{" EXCLUDEINFO " link ToolTypes.ExcludeInfo} tooltype to remove it from the final reply.

      ·  Also, to use IceIQle's wordwrapping, set AmiQWK's Wrap/Trunc
         gadget to Wrap, and set the value to 99. This way, IceIQle's
         wordwrapping feature will work properly.

      ·  Then setup the @{" HEADER " link ToolTypes.Header} and @{" TAGLINE " link ToolTypes.TagLine} tooltypes as described in
         the TOOLTYPES section of this document.

@endnode

@node Installation.OLR "IceIQle, Installation: OLR"
IceOLR Installation

      · Insert the path and filename of IceIQle in IceOLR's EDITOR= tooltype
        just before the editor name like:

            EDITOR=IceTERM:IceIQle TextEditor EditorArgs

        (The full path to IceIQle need not be specified if IceIQle is on the
         search path)
        The 'EditorArgs' part is any option you want to send to your
        TextEditor, for example forcing it to appear on a public screen.

      · Make sure there is NO quote string used in IceOLR. Either make
        sure the (Quote/Header/Both/None) gadget is snapshotted into
        either the 'Header' or 'None' state (ie. NSQUOTE=0 or 2), or
        delete the string entirely for the '>' gadget.

        IceIQle WON'T work properly if you have a quote string defined.

      · If you intend to use IceIQle's customizable header strings, you
        should make sure the gadget described above is in the 'None' state,
        (NSQUOTE=0), then setup a valid HEADER tooltype in IceIQle
        (described later).

@endnode

@node Installation.Other "IceIQle, Installation: Other"
Generic Message Reader Installation

      · Change the Editor setup configuration of your message reader to
        call IceIQle, but leave the editor name in as well.
        For example, with

             Spot1.2d,  set the editor configuration to:
                   IceIQle Editor %s

        Specify the full path to IceIQle, or make sure it's on the
        search path.
        Any other message reader that calls an external text editor
        should work similarly.

      · Create a QUOTING=OFF tooltype in IceIQle's icon.

      · Then setup the @{" TAGLINE " link ToolTypes.TagLine} tooltype as described in the TOOLTYPES
        section of this document.

@endnode

@node Installation.TERM "IceIQle, Installation: TERM"
IceTerm Installation

      · Do the same steps as for using with IceOLR, only with IceTERM's
        icon.

@endnode

@node ToolTypes.AppendLines "IceIQle, ToolTypes: AppendLines"
   APPENDLINES    (Integer)
      Number of newline characters to append to the original
      message. A value > 0 allows quick cursor down (or page down) to
      get to the end of the message without having to move to the end
      of the last line and press return. These lines won't be appended
      for new posts. If you're using the @{" TAGLINE " link ToolTypes.TagLine} tooltype you don't
      really need any APPENDLINES because you can do the formatting
      with the TAGLINE= tooltype.

@endnode

@node ToolTypes.CleanUp "IceIQle, ToolTypes: CleanUp"
   CLEANUP        (BOOLEAN)    [IceBBS and AmiQWK Only]
      If set to TRUE, some blank lines that got initial quoted are
      converted back to an empty line. This makes changes in authors
      easier to identify, and is easier to read. Set this to FALSE and
      you'll probably hate it and discover why I added it (but made
      it an option for the purists).

@endnode

@node ToolTypes.Editor "IceIQle, ToolTypes: Editor"
   EDITOR         (String)
      [Optional - You can more easily include this information in
                  the IceOLR and IceTERM icons - See @{" INSTALLATION " link Doc.Installation}]
      Filename (and path) of text editor you use for editing messages.
      This tooltype will only be used if no editor is given in OLR or TERM.

@endnode

@node ToolTypes.ExcludeInfo "IceIQle, ToolTypes: ExcludeInfo"
   EXCLUDEINFO    (Multiple string)
      List of strings separated by '|' characters.
      Any line STARTING with one of these strings will be deleted
      before the editor is called. This is primarily intended to
      conveniently remove the info lines such as Author, Creation
      Date, etc. Only the first @{" EXCLUDENUM " link ToolTypes.ExcludeNum} number of lines will be
      examined (to avoid the slim possibility of accidently deleting
      a line in the message which might start with 'Author:' or
      similar). The icon is initialized with the value of

         EXCLUDEINFO=Author:|Creation Date:|Address:|Subject:|Old Subject:

      You could add any of the additional items that show up when you
      have the net button activated, or From:|Date: for eliminating the
      info in EMailed messages. No spaces can occur between the strings
      you want excluded and the '|' characters.

      To remove the header from an AmiQWK reply, use:

         EXCLUDEINFO=From:|  To:|Subj:|===========
                           ^^
                     (2 Spaces above required)

@endnode

@node ToolTypes.ExcludeNum "IceIQle, ToolTypes: ExcludeNum"
   EXCLUDENUM     (Integer  -  Default: 8)
      Number of lines to examine for possible exclusion based on the
      @{" EXCLUDEINFO " link ToolTypes.ExcludeInfo} tooltype.

@endnode

@node ToolTypes.Header "IceIQle, ToolTypes: Header"
   HEADER         (String)    [IceBBS and AmiQWK Only]
      Used to define a header string with embedded author, date,
      subject, etc. Special characters preceded by the '%' character
      indicate the appropriate item. There are @{" Name/Date controls " link Embed.DateNameControls} as
      well as @{" Custom controls " link Embed.CustomControls}.

      When defining the HEADER string, you can mix your own text
      with the control codes.

          EXAMPLE 1)

            HEADER=On %w %y-%m-%d %a and %r were discussing:%n  "%s"

            would result in something like:

            On Tue 94-Feb-1 Bryan Ewert and Ken Pierce were discussing:
              "Am I seeing Double, Triple or more?"

      See the @{" TAGLINE " link ToolTypes.TagLine} tooltype, which works identically to HEADER, for
      a more complex example.
@endnode

@node ToolTypes.Header2 "IceIQle, ToolTypes: Header2"
   HEADER2        (String)    [IceBBS and AmiQWK Only]
      Works identically to @{" HEADER " link ToolTypes.Header} but is used when there is no 'Address'
      person OR when the 'Address' field is 'All'.
      This is to give a little more flexibility in defining quote strings
      without having replies to an initial post sound awkward. If using
      a text file (with %S or %R), it would of course make sense to use
      a different file here than for the HEADER= tooltype.
      If HEADER2 isn't specified, @{" HEADER " link ToolTypes.Header} will be used.

@endnode

@node ToolTypes.HeaderMail "IceIQle, ToolTypes: HeaderMail"
   HEADERMAIL     (String)    [IceBBS Only]
      Works identically to @{" HEADER " link ToolTypes.Header} but is used only for EMail messages...
      perhaps to give that more personal touch? Or maybe a more nasty
      edge?
      If HEADERMAIL is not specified, @{" HEADER2 " link ToolTypes.Header2} will be used for EMail.

@endnode

@node ToolTypes.Omit "IceIQle, ToolTypes: Omit"
   OMIT           (Multiple String)
     List of strings separated by '|' characters.
     Any file sent to IceIQle whose name STARTS with one of these strings
     will not be processed at all by IceIQle, but rather is passed on
     unchanged to your editor. The most useful filename to OMIT is
     'tempfiledesc' which is the temp file used when entering the long
     description of an uploaded file. The possible IceBBS filenames are:

             tempnewfile    ->  Feedback Posts.
             tempfile       ->  Feedback Replies.
             tempfiledesc   ->  Long description of uploaded file.
             tempmailfile   ->  EMail Posts.
             tempEMailReply ->  EMail Replies.
             tempimailfile  ->  Internet mail.
             newpost        ->  IceOLR posts or replies.
                                (Random or maybe encoded date/time numbers
                                 are used for On-Line SIG replies/posts)

@endnode

@node ToolTypes.PhraseDir "IceIQle, ToolTypes: PhraseDir"
   PHRASEDIR      (String)
      The directory where you have your phrase text files situated. Used
      for header, tagline and signature files, specifically the %C, %I, %R,
      %S and %V controls. This directory is used only if you don't specify
      the full path in the FileName of these controls.

@endnode

@node ToolTypes.Quoting "IceIQle, ToolTypes: Quoting"
   QUOTING        (Switch  -  Default: ON)
      Enables or Disables the initialed quoting mechanism. Set to OFF
      to completely disable quoting.

@endnode

@node ToolTypes.TagLine "IceIQle, ToolTypes: TagLine"
   TAGLINE        (String)
      Works identically to @{" HEADER " link ToolTypes.Header} with any @{" Name/Date controls " link Embed.DateNameControls} and
      @{" Custom controls " link Embed.CustomControls} but is included at the end of the message.
      For example, assuming the file "JRsSignature" contains simply,
      "Jeff Rose 8^)", and the start of phrases in the text file
      "JRsTags" are identified with the '@' character:

            TAGLINE=%nTTYL %F,%n%n%C"JRsSignature"%n%n...%R@"JRsTags"

      would result in something like:

            TTYL Kevin,

            Jeff Rose 8^)

            ... I am Homer of Borg.  Prepare to be assim...Mmmm, donuts.

      The 'Homer of Borg' tagline would be extracted randomly since the
      %R control was used.
      In this case, it would be easier to simply include the "Jeff Rose 8^)"
      part directly in the TAGLINE= tooltype, however for illustration
      purposes this gives you the idea. More complex signatures would be
      easier to edit in a text file. Also, WorkBench limits you to 128
      characters in tooltype strings.

@endnode

@node ToolTypes.TagMail "IceIQle, ToolTypes: TagMail"
   TAGMAIL        (String)    [IceBBS Only]
      Works identically to @{" TAGLINE " link ToolTypes.TagLine} but is used for local EMail messages
      only. If TAGMAIL is not specified, TAGLINE will be used for EMail.

@endnode

@node ToolTypes.WordWrap "IceIQle, ToolTypes: WordWrap"
   WORDWRAP       (Integer  -  default: 0 / OFF)    [IceBBS/AmiQWK]
   WRAPMARGIN     (Integer  -  default: 15)
      These two items control handling of automatic word-wrap when quoting
      unquoted text only. Anything already quoted is left alone. Works great
      for replying to people who compose messages with Picasso boards! 
      If WORDWRAP is set to zero, or the tooltype isn't present, this
      feature is disabled. Setting WORDWRAP to any other value indicates at
      what column a word is considered to be too far to the right after
      being quoted with initials, and will be moved down to the next line
      when quoted. Paragraphs are NOT hopelessly fragmented by the process,
      but rather are shuffled appropriately to maintain readability. If the
      entire original paragraph was indented by a constant value, it will
      remain that way even after being word-wrapped.

      WORDWRAP must be a minimum of 60. If it isn't, 60 will be used.
      A value of 78 insures words are always visible when using IceOLR or
      your editor to read a quoted message, assuming a standard 640 pixel
      wide screen with an 8 point wide font.

      Since every message already has carriage returns at the end of every
      line, doing word wrap is a little tricky because it can be difficult
      to identify end of paragraphs where you don't want the next line to
      be merged at the end of a paragraph. This is what the WRAPMARGIN
      value is for. Any message line that has the carriage return at a
      column LESS than WORDWRAP - WRAPMARGIN will be considered to be an
      end of paragraph. This means that its carriage return will be left
      in tact at the position that it's in. It is possible for a paragraph
      to end beyond this region, in which case, if both of the following
      conditions AREN'T true, the next paragraph could get joined with the
      current paragraph.

         A) There are 2 CR's separating paragraphs.
         B) The first line of the next paragraph is indented further
            than the current line.

      Any paragraphs separated by either A) or B) will ALWAYS be handled
      correctly, regardless of the WRAPMARGIN setting.
      Also, any line which does not end up getting split up in the word
      wrap process, will have its carriage return left in tact.
      A value of 15 gives good end of paragraph recognition. WRAPMARGIN
      defaults to 15 if not specified in a tooltype. Too small a number
      will cause too many misidentifications of end of paragraph.
      Too high, and paragraphs which are obviously ended, will not be
      considered so.

      The only other possible problem with using wordwrap is when replying
      to a message that has aligned numbers or something past the WORDWRAP
      column. They will of course get pushed down to the next line.

@endnode

